latestIgtvVideos.title: Iced Matcha Latte 🍵
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Hi! From a poll I had my story a few weeks ago, a lottt of people wanted to see a recipe video for my daily matcha latte. Honestly Bal makes this better than me lol and he’s the one who usually makes ours everyday. By no means is this the traditional and therefore right preparation of this delicious tea, but for a latte, I think we do pretty well.

We buy our matcha from sazentea , which is directly from Japan to ensure quality + authenticity and of course to support the Japanese business. Here I am using ‘organic gin matcha’. It is ceremonial grade and very potent! (Tip: your matcha should be vibrant green!)

Matcha has a lot of health benefits like being high in antioxidants, increasing energy, stimulating metabolism, boosting immune system and so much more.

Let me know how you drink you matcha below 🌿

#recipe #igtv #matcha #matchalatte #plantbased

latestIgtvVideos.title: Haldi Ka Dudh
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Aka “golden latte” but don’t use that term around me lol 🙃

A few people requested my haldi ka dudh recipe, so here it is!

Turmeric has been used for centuries in Ayurveda as a healing and cleansing medicine. It’s the queen of Ayurvedic spices and widely used in South Asian cuisine. It’s proven to be anti-inflammatory, anti-oxidant rich, antibacterial and so much more. I grew up having hardar nu dudh (Gujarati for ‘milk with turmeric’; in Hindi it’s ‘haldi ka dudh’) when I was sick and turmeric powder pressed on any cuts when I got hurt. I still apply turmeric face masks regularly for glowing skin. It truly has strong healing properties. 

Turmeric is better absorbed by the body when paired with black pepper and a fat (hence the coconut oil in this recipe). I’ve made it vegan because I follow a vegan diet but many people use ghee, too. 

I usually drink at night as it aids in a good night’s sleep but when I cut caffeine for some time last year, I had it in the mornings too!

Let me know if you try it out 💛

latestIgtvVideos.title: Seed Cycling Chia Seed Pudding
latestIgtvVideos.caption:
Made another IGTV recipe video 🤪

Seed Cycling Chia Seed Pudding — Luteal Phase

I’ve been practicing seed cycling for almost a year now and it has made such an impact in balancing my hormones + regulating my cycle. Seed cycling is a practice that is said to help balance a woman’s hormones and help with fatigue, hair and skin health, water retention, etc.

It divided by two phases: follicular phase (days 1-13 of your cycle) and luteal phase (days 14-28 of your cycle). While this is specifically for menstruating women, all of these seeds have so many health benefits regardless so anyone can eat it! 
The luteal phase involves eating 1 tbsp of raw white sesame seeds + 1 tbsp of raw sunflower seeds per day. For this recipe, I used some tahini and then added some raw sesame seeds to my veggie bowl during lunch to get about 1 tbsp of sesame seeds in for the day. 
I’ll make a video on the follicular phase soon; it involves eating 1 tbsp ground flax seeds + 1 tbsp raw pumpkin seeds per day.

I have my chia seed pudding everyday after my morning green smoothie (IGTV video posted a few weeks ago!). It’s super high in fiber + protein so it’s filling and follows food pairing principles, which aid in digestion and gut health 😊

#recipe#vegan#chiaseeds#seedcycling#ayurvedic#consciouscooking#ayurvediccooking#plantbased#recipes
